comment:
Nike, listen up! Here is what you need to focus on: The customer! 
I buy several pairs of running shoes every year. I will only buy in a brick-and-mortar store after trying them on because I am slightly older and only shoes with a great fit and the right amount of cushioning and stability will enable me to run and walk safely and pain free. Despite living in a reasonably large city (300K residents) I have in recent years not been able to lay my hands on any of your more premium offerings. I am not talking about the lifestyle/fashion stuff here. I have several sports retailers available, but they only carry very limited supplies of Nike, at best one or two of the models that would be of interest to me, and my size, which is very common, is almost always out of stock. I know that Nike makes some great shoes, but I would have to travel hundreds of miles to find a store with a full selection. So my money has gone to Brooks, Asics and Hoka, despite having a lot of respect for Nike.
title: How Nike’s New CEO Plans To Turn Things Around

comment: I feel like the album is titled blonde because blonde hair is often bright when one is young, but it begins to darken as they age. I feel like this is used to discuss how we lose our freedom with age. After the nights beat switch, the album takes a darker tone. In the first half of the album (before nights) frank uses high-pitched vocals to represent his younger self. he also mentions the word summer several times in this album which usually represent youth and freedom. In the second half of the album (after the nights beat switch) he only references summer once when Andre 3000 says he is “watching the summer come close to an end” which sounds like a representation of the end of his childhood.

comment:
I’m truly humbled by the overwhelming response to this video—thank you all for watching, sharing, and caring deeply about these issues. I wanted to address some of the most common comments:

1)To those asking about my safety: Thank you for your concern! I’m completely safe. ☺ Many of the issues discussed in this video are already openly debated on Chinese social media, and I actually drew a lot of insights from those discussions while making this video.

2) Will there be more investigations like this? Honestly, I’m not sure. While I believe in shedding light on these topics, I also recognize that labor conditions in global manufacturing—not just at Shein—are deeply tied to complex supply and demand forces. Real change takes time.

3)To those rethinking their shopping habits: It means so much to hear that this video has made some of you more aware. If there’s one takeaway, it’s that ALL fast fashion—not just Shein—often relies on labor conditions that may be far worse than what most consumers realize.

Again, thank you for engaging with this discussion so thoughtfully. Your comments have given me a lot to reflect on!🙂
title: Inside Shein’s factory village

comment: Thank you for doing this work and sharing this story. Unethical labor practices is an issue I wish ppl would speak up about everywhere. Nothing beats combating issues from the source. As someone who has struggled in their own field with corporations not willing to pay their employees fair wages I feel this personally. I think as consumers we need to be aware of the work that goes into supplying us our needs/wants. Ppl need to be willing to pay real life value even if it is more expensive and companies need to be willingly to pay their workers actual livable wages and cover health and hazards. Fueling dangerous work environment that literally cause injury on top of it is just wrong. This isn’t to say that they shouldn’t work or that we should put them out of business, because that isn’t fair to them. However, a change needs to happen.
title: Inside Shein’s factory village

comment: As someone who is a tailor and works in the fashion industry, it always shocks me how people can still defend such companies while also having no grasp of how much work it actually is to make a garment. Many people treat their clothes like throw-away items that are used only once or twice. But clothes are meant to last for years, they are made for you to spend your life in them, not just one party night.
title: Inside Shein’s factory village
